	<div class="commentBody">
		<div id="comment_body_64248702"><p>I came here to say the same thing.  Cooling the PV cells makes them more efficient, just like water cooling your CPU/GPU helps keep them in their optimum temperature range.</p><p>Actually, the best time to cool the PV cells is when the sun is at its strongest, so summer would actually be the best boost for the cells efficiency.  In the winter, if the sun is less strong or the temperature falls below freezing, you automatically divert and drain the system until it is beneficial again.</p><p><span class="substr"> </span> <a href="https://link.springer.com/article/10.1007/s11356-022-18719-9" title="springer.com">https://link.springer.com/arti.</a> [springer.com]</p></div>
